HEADWORD: Inthrall
<hw>In*thrall"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Inthralled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Inthralling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf.
<er>Enthrall</er>.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also <asp>inthral</asp>,
<asp>enthral</asp>, and <asp>enthrall</asp>.]</altsp> <def>To reduce to
bondage or servitude; to make a thrall, slave, vassal, or captive of; to
enslave.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She soothes, but never can <qex>inthrall</qex> my mind.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inthrallment</ent>⟦br⟧
